  <h2>Spay & Neuter Surgery at Healthy Paws Animal Hospital</h2>
  <p>
    Spaying or neutering your pet is one of the most important health decisions you'll make as a pet owner. At Healthy Paws Animal Hospital in Lake in the Hills, IL, we perform spay and neuter surgeries with the same level of care, precision, and compassion that we bring to every procedure — including our <a href="/low-stress-vet-lake-in-the-hills-il/">gentle, low-stress approach</a> that keeps your pet calm and comfortable from drop-off to pickup.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Spaying and Neutering Matters</h2>
  <p>
    Beyond helping control the pet population, spaying and neutering provides real, measurable health benefits for your individual pet.
  </p>

  <h3>Benefits for Female Pets (Spay)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Eliminates the risk of pyometra</strong> — a life-threatening uterine infection that affects roughly 25% of unspayed female dogs</li>
    <li><strong>Significantly reduces mammary cancer risk</strong> — especially when performed before the first heat cycle</li>
    <li>Eliminates heat cycles, which cause behavioral changes and attract unwanted male attention</li>
    <li>Prevents unwanted pregnancies and the associated health risks of carrying and delivering a litter</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Benefits for Male Pets (Neuter)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Eliminates the risk of testicular cancer</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Reduces the risk of prostate disease</strong></li>
    <li>Decreases roaming behavior — neutered males are far less likely to escape looking for a mate</li>
    <li>Reduces territorial marking and certain aggression behaviors</li>
    <li>Can help with unwanted mounting behavior</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to Expect: Before, During & After Surgery</h2>

  <h3>Pre-Surgical Consultation</h3>
  <p>
    Every spay or neuter at Healthy Paws begins with a <strong>pre-surgical health assessment</strong>. We'll perform a physical exam and run <a href="/laboratory-diagnostics/">pre-surgical bloodwork</a> to evaluate your pet's liver and kidney function, check blood cell counts, and confirm they're healthy enough for anesthesia. This step is essential — it catches hidden health issues that could complicate surgery and lets us customize the anesthesia plan for your pet.
  </p>

  <h3>The Day of Surgery</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Morning drop-off</strong> — you'll bring your pet in first thing in the morning after an overnight fast (we'll give you specific instructions)</li>
    <li><strong>Pre-surgical prep</strong> — your pet receives a calming pre-anesthetic medication as part of our low-stress protocol, along with a pre-operative pain injection so they're comfortable before the procedure even begins</li>
    <li><strong>Continuous monitoring</strong> — throughout surgery, a dedicated technician monitors your pet's heart rate, blood oxygen, blood pressure, and body temperature</li>
    <li><strong>The procedure</strong> — our experienced veterinary team performs the surgery using modern surgical techniques and sterile protocols</li>
    <li><strong>Recovery</strong> — your pet wakes up in a warm, quiet recovery area under close supervision. Most pets go home the same day</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Post-Operative Care</h3>
  <p>
    We send every surgical patient home with a <strong>comprehensive pain management plan</strong>. Your pet shouldn't have to "tough it out" — proper pain control actually speeds healing. You'll receive:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Pain medication to give at home for the first several days</li>
    <li>An e-collar or surgical suit to prevent licking at the incision</li>
    <li>Detailed written instructions for at-home care</li>
    <li>A scheduled follow-up appointment to check the incision and remove sutures</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When to Spay or Neuter Your Pet</h2>
  <p>
    Timing matters, and the right age for spaying or neutering depends on your pet's species, breed, and size.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cats:</strong> Typically spayed or neutered around <strong>5-6 months</strong> of age</li>
    <li><strong>Small to medium dogs:</strong> Usually recommended between <strong>6-9 months</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Large and giant breed dogs:</strong> May benefit from waiting until <strong>12-18 months</strong> to allow for complete skeletal and joint development</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    During your pet's <a href="/wellness-exams-lake-in-the-hills-il/">wellness exam</a>, Dr. Burgess or one of our veterinarians will discuss the ideal timing based on your pet's specific needs. There's no one-size-fits-all answer, and we'll help you make the decision that's best for your individual pet.
  </p>

  <h2>Low-Stress Surgical Care</h2>
  <p>
    Surgery is stressful enough without adding unnecessary fear and anxiety to the experience. Our <a href="/low-stress-vet-lake-in-the-hills-il/">gentle, low-stress</a> approach applies to surgical patients too:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Calming pheromone diffusers in pre-op and recovery areas</li>
    <li>Pre-anesthetic sedation that reduces anxiety <em>before</em> your pet even knows what's happening</li>
    <li>Gentle handling throughout the entire process — from the moment you drop off to the moment you pick up</li>
    <li>A quiet, comfortable recovery space where your pet can wake up without being startled or overwhelmed</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Experienced Surgical Team</h2>
  <p>
    Our veterinarians — including Dr. Burgess, Dr. Haslitt, and Dr. Mosier — have performed thousands of spay and neuter surgeries. You can trust that your pet is in experienced, compassionate hands. We use modern <a href="/surgery/">surgical techniques</a>, advanced monitoring equipment, and individualized anesthesia protocols to ensure the safest possible outcome.
  </p>

